WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.939 align:middle line:90%


00:00:10.939 --> 00:00:13.480 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA GARR: Hi, I'm Lisa Garr,
host of "Gaiam Inspirations."

00:00:13.480 --> 00:00:16.040 align:middle line:10%
We are broadcasting from
beautiful downtown Denver

00:00:16.040 --> 00:00:18.580 align:middle line:10%
at the Hay House "I
Can Do It!" conference.

00:00:18.580 --> 00:00:20.400 align:middle line:10%
So did you know
that the number one

00:00:20.400 --> 00:00:25.510 align:middle line:10%
goal that people have
worldwide is to be happy?

00:00:25.510 --> 00:00:27.450 align:middle line:90%
So are you happy?

00:00:27.450 --> 00:00:31.270 align:middle line:84%
Does the phrase "life, liberty,
and the pursuit of happiness"

00:00:31.270 --> 00:00:34.050 align:middle line:90%
mean that we don't have it?

00:00:34.050 --> 00:00:35.590 align:middle line:90%
What does that really mean?

00:00:35.590 --> 00:00:38.030 align:middle line:84%
So joining me today is
psychologist and the director

00:00:38.030 --> 00:00:40.650 align:middle line:84%
of the Happiness
Project, Robert Holden.

00:00:40.650 --> 00:00:43.680 align:middle line:84%
He's been teaching people all
over the world about happiness

00:00:43.680 --> 00:00:45.020 align:middle line:90%
for 15 years.

00:00:45.020 --> 00:00:47.000 align:middle line:84%
He teaches a course
called Be Happy.

00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:49.600 align:middle line:84%
It's a course with a set
of scientific principles

00:00:49.600 --> 00:00:52.950 align:middle line:84%
and exercises that have been
called a genuine fast track

00:00:52.950 --> 00:00:53.600 align:middle line:90%
to happiness.

00:00:53.600 --> 00:00:55.800 align:middle line:84%
Wouldn't you like to do
that a little bit more?

00:00:55.800 --> 00:00:56.870 align:middle line:90%
Welcome to the show.

00:00:56.870 --> 00:00:57.745 align:middle line:90%
>>ROBERT HOLDEN: Yay.

00:00:57.745 --> 00:00:59.090 align:middle line:90%
Thank you very much, Lisa.

00:00:59.090 --> 00:01:02.247 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So happiness--
why teach about happiness?

00:01:02.247 --> 00:01:04.580 align:middle line:84%
>>HOLDEN: Because it's what
we want, just like you said.

00:01:04.580 --> 00:01:05.663 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Like I said, yeah.

00:01:05.663 --> 00:01:08.420 align:middle line:10%
>>HOLDEN: You know, when you ask
people all over the world, what

00:01:08.420 --> 00:01:11.990 align:middle line:10%
is it you most want, number
one answer is happiness.

00:01:11.990 --> 00:01:14.620 align:middle line:10%
When you ask people all
over the world, what

00:01:14.620 --> 00:01:16.750 align:middle line:10%
is you most want
for your children,

00:01:16.750 --> 00:01:18.870 align:middle line:10%
number one answer is happiness.

00:01:18.870 --> 00:01:20.310 align:middle line:10%
It's just in us.

00:01:20.310 --> 00:01:22.030 align:middle line:10%
We want that experience
of happiness.

00:01:22.030 --> 00:01:25.075 align:middle line:10%
It's there from the beginning,
and it's always on our mind.

00:01:25.075 --> 00:01:26.450 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: But why
don't we have it?

00:01:26.450 --> 00:01:29.270 align:middle line:84%
Why are we always in pursuit
of it, like the phrase says,

00:01:29.270 --> 00:01:31.685 align:middle line:84%
at least in America, that
"pursuit of happiness?"

00:01:31.685 --> 00:01:33.310 align:middle line:84%
>>HOLDEN: Yeah, isn't
that interesting?

00:01:33.310 --> 00:01:35.630 align:middle line:84%
Something's happened along
the way where we clearly

00:01:35.630 --> 00:01:37.705 align:middle line:84%
got a little bit
confused, haven't we?

00:01:37.705 --> 00:01:39.622 align:middle line:84%
Let's take that phrase
"pursuit of happiness,"

00:01:39.622 --> 00:01:40.955 align:middle line:90%
because it's really interesting.

00:01:40.955 --> 00:01:41.740 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: It is.

00:01:41.740 --> 00:01:43.323 align:middle line:84%
>>HOLDEN: Yeah.
"Pursuit of happiness"

00:01:43.323 --> 00:01:44.674 align:middle line:90%
has potentially two meanings.

00:01:44.674 --> 00:01:46.090 align:middle line:84%
Well, it's really
down to the word

00:01:46.090 --> 00:01:48.570 align:middle line:84%
"pursuit," because
"pursuit" can either

00:01:48.570 --> 00:01:51.992 align:middle line:90%
mean to take an interest in--

00:01:51.992 --> 00:01:53.575 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: OK, meaning
you don't have it.

00:01:53.575 --> 00:01:55.197 align:middle line:90%
>>HOLDEN: --or to chase it.

00:01:55.197 --> 00:01:55.780 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:01:55.780 --> 00:01:58.380 align:middle line:84%
>>HOLDEN: Now, for
me, to have the right

00:01:58.380 --> 00:01:59.970 align:middle line:84%
to take an interest
in happiness,

00:01:59.970 --> 00:02:03.140 align:middle line:84%
to have the right to
inquire into the true nature

00:02:03.140 --> 00:02:05.750 align:middle line:84%
of happiness, that's
a beautiful thing.

00:02:05.750 --> 00:02:09.440 align:middle line:84%
But to chase happiness,
that's where,

00:02:09.440 --> 00:02:12.120 align:middle line:84%
for me, the great mistake
lies, because the moment

00:02:12.120 --> 00:02:14.620 align:middle line:84%
you think you have
to chase happiness,

00:02:14.620 --> 00:02:17.770 align:middle line:84%
I believe you have misunderstood
what true happiness is.

00:02:17.770 --> 00:02:20.520 align:middle line:84%
So right there in that
phrase and in that word

00:02:20.520 --> 00:02:23.940 align:middle line:84%
"pursuit," is almost like
where we've got two roads.

00:02:23.940 --> 00:02:26.970 align:middle line:84%
We could either get really
interested in what happiness is

00:02:26.970 --> 00:02:29.870 align:middle line:84%
and get clear on what
it is, or we go chasing.

00:02:29.870 --> 00:02:32.120 align:middle line:84%
And it's because we go
chasing that I think,

00:02:32.120 --> 00:02:35.760 align:middle line:84%
actually, the road to happiness
becomes a never-ending road.

00:02:35.760 --> 00:02:37.390 align:middle line:90%
We never actually get that.

00:02:37.390 --> 00:02:39.119 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: It is
interesting, because it's

00:02:39.119 --> 00:02:40.160 align:middle line:90%
on the Statue of Liberty.

00:02:40.160 --> 00:02:42.880 align:middle line:84%
And it says, we have
life, we have liberty,

00:02:42.880 --> 00:02:44.270 align:middle line:90%
but we don't have happiness.

00:02:44.270 --> 00:02:45.400 align:middle line:90%
That's what it says.

00:02:45.400 --> 00:02:47.860 align:middle line:84%
To me, it says that
we don't have it.

00:02:47.860 --> 00:02:48.485 align:middle line:90%
>>HOLDEN: Yeah.

00:02:48.485 --> 00:02:50.420 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: It is
outside of ourselves.

00:02:50.420 --> 00:02:53.010 align:middle line:84%
>>HOLDEN: That's the great
mistake that we make.

00:02:53.010 --> 00:02:56.300 align:middle line:84%
And so when I created
the Happiness Project,

00:02:56.300 --> 00:02:59.200 align:middle line:84%
initially, part of the reasoning
for creating the project

00:02:59.200 --> 00:03:03.720 align:middle line:84%
was because I realized I didn't
know anything about happiness.

00:03:03.720 --> 00:03:05.900 align:middle line:84%
I'd been trained
as a psychologist.

00:03:05.900 --> 00:03:07.730 align:middle line:90%
I'd been trained in philosophy.

00:03:07.730 --> 00:03:12.010 align:middle line:84%
And in my entire training was
really a study of unhappiness.

00:03:12.010 --> 00:03:15.055 align:middle line:84%
So I was looking at all the
reasons why we're unhappy.

00:03:15.055 --> 00:03:17.660 align:middle line:84%
And one day, it
occurred to me, maybe

00:03:17.660 --> 00:03:21.260 align:middle line:84%
we're unhappy because we
don't know what happiness is.

00:03:21.260 --> 00:03:24.110 align:middle line:84%
In six years of study,
I only had one lecture

00:03:24.110 --> 00:03:25.890 align:middle line:90%
on happiness, only one lecture.

00:03:25.890 --> 00:03:26.646 align:middle line:90%
That's not much.

00:03:26.646 --> 00:03:28.270 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: In London is
where you studied?

00:03:28.270 --> 00:03:28.710 align:middle line:90%
>>HOLDEN: Actually, no.

00:03:28.710 --> 00:03:30.110 align:middle line:84%
I studied in the
middle of England,

00:03:30.110 --> 00:03:31.270 align:middle line:90%
in a place called Birmingham.

00:03:31.270 --> 00:03:31.770 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:03:31.770 --> 00:03:35.190 align:middle line:84%
>>HOLDEN: But fundamentally,
the entire study,

00:03:35.190 --> 00:03:37.790 align:middle line:84%
if I was to break it down for
you, year one and year two

00:03:37.790 --> 00:03:40.630 align:middle line:90%
was Introductory Suffering.

00:03:40.630 --> 00:03:43.590 align:middle line:84%
Year three and year four
was Advanced Suffering.

00:03:43.590 --> 00:03:47.300 align:middle line:84%
Year five and year six
was Inspired Suffering.

00:03:47.300 --> 00:03:49.040 align:middle line:84%
Everything we
studied in psychology

00:03:49.040 --> 00:03:51.970 align:middle line:84%
was problems-- diagnoses,
problems, unhappiness.

00:03:51.970 --> 00:03:53.880 align:middle line:90%
Now, that's a good study.

00:03:53.880 --> 00:03:57.910 align:middle line:84%
But fundamentally, the thing
we missed was happiness.

00:03:57.910 --> 00:04:00.040 align:middle line:84%
And it just occurred
to me that actually,

00:04:00.040 --> 00:04:02.050 align:middle line:84%
maybe the whole
reason we're unhappy

00:04:02.050 --> 00:04:05.590 align:middle line:84%
is because we're not clear
what real happiness is.

00:04:05.590 --> 00:04:08.280 align:middle line:84%
That's been, basically,
the fundamental basis

00:04:08.280 --> 00:04:10.860 align:middle line:84%
of my work with the
Happiness Project.

00:04:10.860 --> 00:04:14.220 align:middle line:84%
My feeling is is that most
people don't need more therapy.

00:04:14.220 --> 00:04:16.399 align:middle line:90%
What they need is more clarity.

00:04:16.399 --> 00:04:18.829 align:middle line:84%
And when we have
more clarity, that

00:04:18.829 --> 00:04:20.920 align:middle line:90%
becomes incredibly therapeutic.

00:04:20.920 --> 00:04:24.540 align:middle line:84%
That helps us to understand
not just what happiness is,

00:04:24.540 --> 00:04:25.250 align:middle line:90%
but who we are.

00:04:25.250 --> 00:04:27.440 align:middle line:84%
And when we get
clear, that's when

00:04:27.440 --> 00:04:28.847 align:middle line:90%
I think we get to be happier.

00:04:28.847 --> 00:04:30.180 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Well, it's a good point.

00:04:30.180 --> 00:04:32.840 align:middle line:84%
I was doing some research before
the interview on forbes.com.

00:04:32.840 --> 00:04:37.340 align:middle line:84%
And it said that America is
actually ranked 11th overall--

00:04:37.340 --> 00:04:39.930 align:middle line:84%
and this changes all the
time, but recently-- overall

00:04:39.930 --> 00:04:42.880 align:middle line:84%
in terms of the world's
happiest countries, Norway

00:04:42.880 --> 00:04:44.230 align:middle line:90%
being number one.

00:04:44.230 --> 00:04:50.110 align:middle line:84%
And they then continued to
relate happiness to money.

00:04:50.110 --> 00:04:53.710 align:middle line:84%
So the more financial status
that a country would have,

00:04:53.710 --> 00:04:58.110 align:middle line:90%
the more happy the people were.

00:04:58.110 --> 00:05:01.071 align:middle line:84%
Why are happiness and
money always linked?

00:05:01.071 --> 00:05:02.820 align:middle line:84%
>>HOLDEN: Well, they're
not always linked.

00:05:02.820 --> 00:05:04.805 align:middle line:84%
It's just that in those
types of studies--

00:05:04.805 --> 00:05:05.930 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: In the media, yeah.

00:05:05.930 --> 00:05:06.210 align:middle line:90%
>>HOLDEN: Yeah.

00:05:06.210 --> 00:05:07.790 align:middle line:84%
In those types of
studies, happiness

00:05:07.790 --> 00:05:12.030 align:middle line:84%
is defined specifically
here as satisfaction.

00:05:12.030 --> 00:05:15.280 align:middle line:84%
Now, again, we have to get clear
on what happiness really is.

00:05:15.280 --> 00:05:18.180 align:middle line:84%
And I would suggest there's
three types of happiness.

00:05:18.180 --> 00:05:20.460 align:middle line:84%
One type of happiness
is pleasure.

00:05:20.460 --> 00:05:26.480 align:middle line:84%
Pleasure is the
enjoyment of the senses.

00:05:26.480 --> 00:05:31.250 align:middle line:84%
It's to do with why I will like
coffee and somebody else won't.

00:05:31.250 --> 00:05:33.630 align:middle line:84%
It's why some of us like
milk chocolate and some of us

00:05:33.630 --> 00:05:34.750 align:middle line:90%
like dark chocolate.

00:05:34.750 --> 00:05:38.560 align:middle line:84%
It's why some of us listen to
Barry Manilow records and some

00:05:38.560 --> 00:05:39.480 align:middle line:90%
of us don't.

00:05:39.480 --> 00:05:43.600 align:middle line:84%
I mean, fundamentally, that
is pleasure and pain happening

00:05:43.600 --> 00:05:44.710 align:middle line:90%
right there.

00:05:44.710 --> 00:05:46.840 align:middle line:84%
And that's one
type of happiness.

00:05:46.840 --> 00:05:49.990 align:middle line:84%
Another type of happiness
is satisfaction.

00:05:49.990 --> 00:05:52.410 align:middle line:90%
I am happy because.

00:05:52.410 --> 00:05:54.880 align:middle line:84%
Now, most happiness
research in the mainstream

00:05:54.880 --> 00:05:56.620 align:middle line:90%
is based around satisfaction.

00:05:56.620 --> 00:05:57.840 align:middle line:90%
I'm happy because.

00:05:57.840 --> 00:06:00.520 align:middle line:84%
And that's an important
type of happiness.

00:06:00.520 --> 00:06:02.770 align:middle line:84%
But there is one other
type of happiness.

00:06:02.770 --> 00:06:06.060 align:middle line:84%
And that type of
happiness I call joy.

00:06:06.060 --> 00:06:09.150 align:middle line:84%
Now, joy is something
else altogether.

00:06:09.150 --> 00:06:13.570 align:middle line:84%
Joy is unreasonable
happiness, because joy

00:06:13.570 --> 00:06:14.980 align:middle line:90%
doesn't need a reason.

00:06:14.980 --> 00:06:16.630 align:middle line:90%
It doesn't need a because.

00:06:16.630 --> 00:06:18.720 align:middle line:84%
It's something
completely different.

00:06:18.720 --> 00:06:22.340 align:middle line:84%
So fundamentally, again,
the most important thing

00:06:22.340 --> 00:06:25.940 align:middle line:84%
is is whenever anybody is
talking about happiness,

00:06:25.940 --> 00:06:29.000 align:middle line:84%
whenever you are talking about
happiness, make sure you know

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:30.760 align:middle line:84%
what you're talking
about, because we all

00:06:30.760 --> 00:06:33.570 align:middle line:84%
have very different definitions
of what happiness is.

00:06:33.570 --> 00:06:36.660 align:middle line:84%
The most important
thing, individually,

00:06:36.660 --> 00:06:38.512 align:middle line:84%
is that we know
what we're talking

00:06:38.512 --> 00:06:40.220 align:middle line:84%
about when we're
talking about happiness.

00:06:40.220 --> 00:06:41.510 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Well, it's
interesting, because there's

00:06:41.510 --> 00:06:43.160 align:middle line:90%
a slew of books on happiness.

00:06:43.160 --> 00:06:44.830 align:middle line:84%
You've done the
study on happiness.

00:06:44.830 --> 00:06:46.690 align:middle line:84%
Talk to us about the
project that you did,

00:06:46.690 --> 00:06:49.910 align:middle line:84%
the Happiness Project, that the
BBC did the documentary around.

00:06:49.910 --> 00:06:50.910 align:middle line:90%
>>HOLDEN: OK, so--

00:06:50.910 --> 00:06:51.420 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Fascinating.

00:06:51.420 --> 00:06:53.461 align:middle line:10%
>>HOLDEN: --when I created
the Happiness Project,

00:06:53.461 --> 00:06:55.530 align:middle line:10%
that was in 1992.

00:06:55.530 --> 00:06:58.100 align:middle line:10%
I created it on the
National Health Service.

00:06:58.100 --> 00:07:02.070 align:middle line:84%
And all the way up until then,
I had been studying unhappiness

00:07:02.070 --> 00:07:05.450 align:middle line:84%
and helping people to try to
get over their unhappiness.

00:07:05.450 --> 00:07:07.530 align:middle line:84%
Basically, the equation
I was working to,

00:07:07.530 --> 00:07:12.940 align:middle line:84%
Lisa, was, if I can help you
get over your unhappiness,

00:07:12.940 --> 00:07:15.350 align:middle line:84%
you will then go
away and be happy.

00:07:15.350 --> 00:07:17.900 align:middle line:90%
That was the deal.

00:07:17.900 --> 00:07:19.206 align:middle line:90%
I never saw it happen.

00:07:19.206 --> 00:07:19.830 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Really?

00:07:19.830 --> 00:07:22.130 align:middle line:84%
>>HOLDEN: I would
help people overcome

00:07:22.130 --> 00:07:25.590 align:middle line:90%
one cause of unhappiness.

00:07:25.590 --> 00:07:28.430 align:middle line:84%
And instead of them then
going away and being happy,

00:07:28.430 --> 00:07:30.570 align:middle line:84%
just before they were
about to be happy,

00:07:30.570 --> 00:07:32.770 align:middle line:90%
another unhappiness came up.

00:07:32.770 --> 00:07:34.830 align:middle line:90%
And another unhappiness came up.

00:07:34.830 --> 00:07:37.220 align:middle line:84%
And so one day I just
decided, you know,

00:07:37.220 --> 00:07:40.160 align:middle line:84%
if we're going to get to
happiness, truly, then

00:07:40.160 --> 00:07:44.160 align:middle line:84%
we mustn't wait until
we're not unhappy.

00:07:44.160 --> 00:07:46.150 align:middle line:84%
What we've got to do
is we've got to say,

00:07:46.150 --> 00:07:48.450 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to explore
happiness now.

00:07:48.450 --> 00:07:51.000 align:middle line:84%
Right in the middle of
the mess of my life,

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:56.140 align:middle line:84%
right in this imperfect moment
that I'm living in, right here,

00:07:56.140 --> 00:07:58.770 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to start to
look at what happiness is.

00:07:58.770 --> 00:08:01.040 align:middle line:84%
And originally, our
first mission statement

00:08:01.040 --> 00:08:04.490 align:middle line:84%
at the Happiness Project
was "talk happiness."

00:08:04.490 --> 00:08:07.280 align:middle line:84%
Let's start talking
about happiness,

00:08:07.280 --> 00:08:09.530 align:middle line:84%
because happiness is
the number one goal.

00:08:09.530 --> 00:08:12.180 align:middle line:84%
But actually, genuinely,
if you ask people, have

00:08:12.180 --> 00:08:14.830 align:middle line:84%
you talked to your parents
ever about happiness,

00:08:14.830 --> 00:08:17.760 align:middle line:84%
have you talked to your
partner ever about happiness,

00:08:17.760 --> 00:08:20.640 align:middle line:84%
have you talked with your
friends ever about happiness,

00:08:20.640 --> 00:08:24.326 align:middle line:84%
the answer is either
"no" or "seldom."

00:08:24.326 --> 00:08:26.200 align:middle line:84%
And in my experience,
one of the first things

00:08:26.200 --> 00:08:28.220 align:middle line:84%
we can do to get really
clear on happiness

00:08:28.220 --> 00:08:29.849 align:middle line:90%
is let's start talking about it.

00:08:29.849 --> 00:08:31.890 align:middle line:84%
Let's start talking about
it with the people that

00:08:31.890 --> 00:08:35.230 align:middle line:84%
matter most to us to see if we
can start to get clear on it.

00:08:35.230 --> 00:08:37.590 align:middle line:84%
So that, for me,
is where you begin.

00:08:37.590 --> 00:08:38.990 align:middle line:90%
And that's where I began.

00:08:38.990 --> 00:08:40.740 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: What did you
find that the biggest

00:08:40.740 --> 00:08:44.360 align:middle line:84%
source of unhappiness
is for people?

00:08:44.360 --> 00:08:45.544 align:middle line:90%
>>HOLDEN: Chasing happiness.

00:08:45.544 --> 00:08:46.585 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That's that, huh?

00:08:46.585 --> 00:08:47.765 align:middle line:90%
It's chasing it.

00:08:47.765 --> 00:08:49.046 align:middle line:90%
>>HOLDEN: Yeah.

00:08:49.046 --> 00:08:50.420 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Unhappiness
sources would

00:08:50.420 --> 00:08:55.660 align:middle line:84%
be loss, a financial
devastation, all those things?

00:08:55.660 --> 00:08:56.950 align:middle line:90%
>>HOLDEN: All of those matter.

00:08:56.950 --> 00:09:00.880 align:middle line:84%
But fundamentally, I created
the Happiness Project

00:09:00.880 --> 00:09:04.620 align:middle line:84%
to help people to give up
the search for happiness,

00:09:04.620 --> 00:09:06.700 align:middle line:84%
because, really, the
search for happiness

00:09:06.700 --> 00:09:08.510 align:middle line:90%
is what causes all of the pain.

00:09:08.510 --> 00:09:12.430 align:middle line:84%
I basically made a
proposition, which

00:09:12.430 --> 00:09:14.480 align:middle line:84%
was that there is a
world of difference

00:09:14.480 --> 00:09:18.830 align:middle line:84%
between the search for happiness
and following your joy, two

00:09:18.830 --> 00:09:20.900 align:middle line:90%
totally different paradigms.

00:09:20.900 --> 00:09:24.790 align:middle line:84%
The search for happiness places
happiness outside of you.

00:09:24.790 --> 00:09:26.500 align:middle line:90%
It becomes a chase.

00:09:26.500 --> 00:09:30.150 align:middle line:84%
And you enter a
paradigm of becoming.

00:09:30.150 --> 00:09:31.670 align:middle line:90%
I'm going to become happy.

00:09:31.670 --> 00:09:35.850 align:middle line:84%
Not yet-- soon, really soon,
hopefully, but not yet.

00:09:35.850 --> 00:09:38.330 align:middle line:84%
And I'm going to have to
chase the happiness in order

00:09:38.330 --> 00:09:40.550 align:middle line:90%
to chase it down.

00:09:40.550 --> 00:09:42.389 align:middle line:84%
Following your joy is
entirely different.

00:09:42.389 --> 00:09:43.930 align:middle line:84%
I don't know if you
can even feel it,

00:09:43.930 --> 00:09:45.180 align:middle line:90%
but it's quite a lovely thing.

00:09:45.180 --> 00:09:47.790 align:middle line:84%
It's like, chasing happiness,
I'm out of breath already.

00:09:47.790 --> 00:09:50.570 align:middle line:84%
Following my joy,
hold on a minute--

00:09:50.570 --> 00:09:53.970 align:middle line:84%
I'm now tuning into something
that's already here.

00:09:53.970 --> 00:09:55.116 align:middle line:90%
It's really cool.

00:09:55.116 --> 00:09:56.490 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: You have
a great exercise

00:09:56.490 --> 00:09:59.850 align:middle line:84%
you took me through before
called "happiness is."

00:09:59.850 --> 00:10:03.010 align:middle line:84%
And you had me repeat this
like 11 times or something.

00:10:03.010 --> 00:10:05.420 align:middle line:84%
And I went through
from giving you

00:10:05.420 --> 00:10:08.280 align:middle line:84%
the textbook answer to
completely crying and then

00:10:08.280 --> 00:10:11.530 align:middle line:84%
going into what
actually what it was.

00:10:11.530 --> 00:10:16.750 align:middle line:84%
And it was, for me, a perfect
example of what you probably

00:10:16.750 --> 00:10:18.320 align:middle line:84%
experience with the
Happiness Project

00:10:18.320 --> 00:10:22.570 align:middle line:84%
as people tell you what they
think it is and then realize

00:10:22.570 --> 00:10:25.130 align:middle line:84%
they don't have it, because
we've been chasing it

00:10:25.130 --> 00:10:27.710 align:middle line:84%
for so long, and then
ultimately understanding

00:10:27.710 --> 00:10:32.710 align:middle line:90%
that it is right here.

00:10:32.710 --> 00:10:36.000 align:middle line:84%
For me, it was the laughter,
that great laughter,

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:39.930 align:middle line:84%
of my child-- that
awesome, incredible sound

00:10:39.930 --> 00:10:42.935 align:middle line:84%
that just reverberates
through my heart.

00:10:42.935 --> 00:10:45.150 align:middle line:84%
It just makes my
whole body tingle.

00:10:45.150 --> 00:10:48.055 align:middle line:90%
And I love that sound.

00:10:48.055 --> 00:10:49.136 align:middle line:90%
>>HOLDEN: I know.

00:10:49.136 --> 00:10:50.260 align:middle line:90%
That's beautiful, isn't it?

00:10:50.260 --> 00:10:50.820 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: It is.

00:10:50.820 --> 00:10:51.320 align:middle line:90%
It is.

00:10:51.320 --> 00:10:54.095 align:middle line:84%
And the funny thing is
that my daughter left me

00:10:54.095 --> 00:10:56.690 align:middle line:84%
a voice message once
on my cell phone.

00:10:56.690 --> 00:10:58.375 align:middle line:84%
And I kept it, because
in the message,

00:10:58.375 --> 00:11:01.320 align:middle line:90%
she was belly laughing so hard.

00:11:01.320 --> 00:11:04.610 align:middle line:84%
And if I'm ever out of
town and away or whatever,

00:11:04.610 --> 00:11:06.310 align:middle line:90%
I'll go back in and I'll listen.

00:11:06.310 --> 00:11:08.100 align:middle line:90%
It takes me right there.

00:11:08.100 --> 00:11:09.110 align:middle line:90%
And that's what it is.

00:11:09.110 --> 00:11:12.000 align:middle line:84%
Happiness is that
feeling of total joy,

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:14.100 align:middle line:84%
like you experience
that elation.

00:11:14.100 --> 00:11:15.620 align:middle line:84%
So in the project,
though, did you

00:11:15.620 --> 00:11:17.860 align:middle line:84%
ever get to that
level with people?

00:11:17.860 --> 00:11:19.102 align:middle line:90%
Did they ever stop chasing?

00:11:19.102 --> 00:11:20.060 align:middle line:90%
>>HOLDEN: All the time.

00:11:20.060 --> 00:11:20.870 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, all the time.

00:11:20.870 --> 00:11:23.160 align:middle line:84%
And what we did was we created
an eight-week happiness

00:11:23.160 --> 00:11:24.090 align:middle line:90%
program.

00:11:24.090 --> 00:11:27.340 align:middle line:84%
Now, that's the program
that's called "Be Happy."

00:11:27.340 --> 00:11:30.600 align:middle line:84%
And that was, I felt, a
good enough amount of time

00:11:30.600 --> 00:11:36.360 align:middle line:84%
to help people really make that
shift from chasing happiness

00:11:36.360 --> 00:11:38.965 align:middle line:90%
to following your joy.

00:11:38.965 --> 00:11:42.800 align:middle line:84%
And we did that over a number
of different exercises.

00:11:42.800 --> 00:11:45.785 align:middle line:84%
But I guess we started with
getting clear on what happiness

00:11:45.785 --> 00:11:51.650 align:middle line:84%
is and just realizing that
happiness isn't outside of us.

00:11:51.650 --> 00:11:53.240 align:middle line:90%
And this is the big thing, Lisa.

00:11:53.240 --> 00:11:55.410 align:middle line:90%
Happiness isn't even inside us.

00:11:55.410 --> 00:11:57.770 align:middle line:84%
We've got to get
closer than that.

00:11:57.770 --> 00:12:01.920 align:middle line:84%
Outside and in is just-- I
call those body metaphors.

00:12:01.920 --> 00:12:04.100 align:middle line:84%
We say "outside"
and "in" because we

00:12:04.100 --> 00:12:05.510 align:middle line:90%
think we're this body.

00:12:05.510 --> 00:12:07.460 align:middle line:84%
Happiness is closer
to you than that.

00:12:07.460 --> 00:12:08.490 align:middle line:90%
It's not outside you.

00:12:08.490 --> 00:12:10.340 align:middle line:90%
It's not inside you.

00:12:10.340 --> 00:12:12.770 align:middle line:90%
It's your true nature.

00:12:12.770 --> 00:12:14.880 align:middle line:84%
The whole reason
we want to be happy

00:12:14.880 --> 00:12:17.710 align:middle line:84%
is because we want
to be ourselves.

00:12:17.710 --> 00:12:20.660 align:middle line:84%
And when we're happy,
we're being ourselves.

00:12:20.660 --> 00:12:24.110 align:middle line:84%
It's the whole reason why,
across all the cultures

00:12:24.110 --> 00:12:28.260 align:middle line:84%
of this planet, the one thing
that we seem to have in common

00:12:28.260 --> 00:12:30.056 align:middle line:84%
is that we want to
be happy, because we

00:12:30.056 --> 00:12:30.930 align:middle line:90%
want to be ourselves.

00:12:30.930 --> 00:12:31.880 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: It's true.

00:12:31.880 --> 00:12:34.680 align:middle line:84%
And when you have that
experience of being yourself,

00:12:34.680 --> 00:12:38.315 align:middle line:84%
if you express fully who
you are, you feel free.

00:12:38.315 --> 00:12:38.940 align:middle line:90%
>>HOLDEN: Yeah.

00:12:38.940 --> 00:12:40.090 align:middle line:90%
It's a fantastic feeling.

00:12:40.090 --> 00:12:43.080 align:middle line:90%
And it's us being authentic.

00:12:43.080 --> 00:12:45.150 align:middle line:84%
So another thing
we look at, Lisa,

00:12:45.150 --> 00:12:47.750 align:middle line:90%
is the purpose of happiness.

00:12:47.750 --> 00:12:51.510 align:middle line:84%
Now, often, this gets
missed in our inquiries.

00:12:51.510 --> 00:12:53.180 align:middle line:84%
You know, I think
the whole reason

00:12:53.180 --> 00:12:57.730 align:middle line:84%
why I didn't have any
good lectures on happiness

00:12:57.730 --> 00:12:59.220 align:middle line:84%
when I was studying
psychology is

00:12:59.220 --> 00:13:01.960 align:middle line:84%
because we didn't understand
the purpose of happiness.

00:13:01.960 --> 00:13:05.970 align:middle line:84%
We just thought happiness was
a pleasurable emotion, a fun

00:13:05.970 --> 00:13:08.170 align:middle line:90%
thing to feel from time to time.

00:13:08.170 --> 00:13:10.130 align:middle line:84%
But I think if we
had understood back

00:13:10.130 --> 00:13:13.650 align:middle line:84%
then the purpose of happiness,
I think we would study it more.

00:13:13.650 --> 00:13:16.480 align:middle line:84%
And I would suggest that
the purpose of happiness

00:13:16.480 --> 00:13:18.980 align:middle line:90%
is to help us to be authentic.

00:13:18.980 --> 00:13:21.740 align:middle line:84%
The whole point of
happiness is to show you

00:13:21.740 --> 00:13:23.670 align:middle line:84%
when you're being
true to yourself.

00:13:23.670 --> 00:13:25.550 align:middle line:84%
When you're being
true to yourself,

00:13:25.550 --> 00:13:30.320 align:middle line:84%
even if it's putting other
people out-- temporarily,

00:13:30.320 --> 00:13:33.420 align:middle line:84%
hopefully-- it's
like we know we're

00:13:33.420 --> 00:13:36.060 align:middle line:84%
sustained by that feeling
of happiness, which says,

00:13:36.060 --> 00:13:41.100 align:middle line:84%
this is true, I'm on track,
I'm being true to myself.

00:13:41.100 --> 00:13:43.640 align:middle line:84%
The purpose of
happiness, it's a light

00:13:43.640 --> 00:13:46.370 align:middle line:84%
on your personal dashboard,
which is basically saying,

00:13:46.370 --> 00:13:48.670 align:middle line:84%
you're on track,
you're doing great.

00:13:48.670 --> 00:13:51.960 align:middle line:84%
Unhappiness, on the other
hand, is often feedback

00:13:51.960 --> 00:13:54.180 align:middle line:84%
that we're not being
true to ourselves.

00:13:54.180 --> 00:13:56.730 align:middle line:84%
And that's why we also have to
pay attention to unhappiness,

00:13:56.730 --> 00:13:59.030 align:middle line:84%
because it's trying to
show us, hold on a minute,

00:13:59.030 --> 00:14:00.090 align:middle line:90%
let's take a moment.

00:14:00.090 --> 00:14:03.810 align:middle line:84%
Let's stop, and let's see how
I can be more true to who I am.

00:14:03.810 --> 00:14:07.084 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Have you been
unhappy in your life?

00:14:07.084 --> 00:14:08.950 align:middle line:90%
>>HOLDEN: Yeah, lots.

00:14:08.950 --> 00:14:10.920 align:middle line:90%
Absolutely.

00:14:10.920 --> 00:14:13.180 align:middle line:84%
It's a feature of the
human condition, isn't it?

00:14:13.180 --> 00:14:15.410 align:middle line:90%
It's right there.

00:14:15.410 --> 00:14:19.150 align:middle line:84%
I guess, in my experience
of unhappiness,

00:14:19.150 --> 00:14:21.480 align:middle line:84%
it originally would
have been actually

00:14:21.480 --> 00:14:23.580 align:middle line:84%
through my relationship
with my parents,

00:14:23.580 --> 00:14:28.320 align:middle line:84%
because my mum had experienced
depression most of her life.

00:14:28.320 --> 00:14:31.270 align:middle line:84%
So I witnessed
this person that I

00:14:31.270 --> 00:14:36.070 align:middle line:84%
loved dearly having this extreme
experience of depression.

00:14:36.070 --> 00:14:37.810 align:middle line:84%
And it was recurrent
depression, Lisa.

00:14:37.810 --> 00:14:43.330 align:middle line:84%
So this is the depression
that happens in episodes.

00:14:43.330 --> 00:14:46.490 align:middle line:84%
It would arrive
often unannounced.

00:14:46.490 --> 00:14:49.720 align:middle line:84%
So it would take her
and us by surprise.

00:14:49.720 --> 00:14:50.990 align:middle line:90%
And then it would settle in.

00:14:50.990 --> 00:14:55.040 align:middle line:84%
And it might settle in for
a day or a week or months.

00:14:55.040 --> 00:14:57.390 align:middle line:84%
And in the really
bad times, she'd

00:14:57.390 --> 00:14:59.790 align:middle line:90%
go away into mental hospitals.

00:14:59.790 --> 00:15:02.650 align:middle line:84%
She would have those
extreme treatments back then

00:15:02.650 --> 00:15:04.900 align:middle line:90%
of electric shock therapy.

00:15:04.900 --> 00:15:07.690 align:middle line:84%
I mean, terrible, terrible,
terrible stuff going on.

00:15:07.690 --> 00:15:10.570 align:middle line:84%
So that was what I was
witnessing in my mum.

00:15:10.570 --> 00:15:13.620 align:middle line:84%
And in my dad, well,
my dad was alcoholic.

00:15:13.620 --> 00:15:17.180 align:middle line:84%
And he left home
when I was about 15.

00:15:17.180 --> 00:15:20.720 align:middle line:84%
And for the last 10
years of his life,

00:15:20.720 --> 00:15:22.620 align:middle line:84%
he lived homeless
a lot of the time.

00:15:22.620 --> 00:15:25.620 align:middle line:84%
So the two people that
I absolutely love,

00:15:25.620 --> 00:15:28.370 align:middle line:84%
the two people that I
know really loved me,

00:15:28.370 --> 00:15:30.850 align:middle line:90%
were battling with these demons.

00:15:30.850 --> 00:15:37.220 align:middle line:84%
And I guess I saw unhappiness
originally through them.

00:15:37.220 --> 00:15:39.430 align:middle line:84%
But of course, I have
my own unhappiness, too.

00:15:39.430 --> 00:15:41.180 align:middle line:84%
But it was right there
from the beginning.

00:15:41.180 --> 00:15:44.000 align:middle line:84%
And in many ways,
that unhappiness

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:47.401 align:middle line:84%
was the catalyst for
wanting me to understand

00:15:47.401 --> 00:15:48.150 align:middle line:90%
what happiness is.

00:15:48.150 --> 00:15:48.900 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Of course.

00:15:48.900 --> 00:15:51.790 align:middle line:84%
It took your parents away
from you in many ways.

00:15:51.790 --> 00:15:52.790 align:middle line:90%
>>HOLDEN: Yeah, exactly.

00:15:52.790 --> 00:15:54.831 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And it would be
that uninvited guest that

00:15:54.831 --> 00:15:56.895 align:middle line:84%
would come in and
take away everything.

00:15:56.895 --> 00:15:58.840 align:middle line:84%
And that is exactly
what depression

00:15:58.840 --> 00:16:02.160 align:middle line:84%
feels like for people, is
it's the uninvited guest that

00:16:02.160 --> 00:16:03.260 align:middle line:90%
comes in and takes over.

00:16:03.260 --> 00:16:04.285 align:middle line:90%
>>HOLDEN: Yeah, exactly.

00:16:04.285 --> 00:16:05.820 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: But it's disabling.

00:16:05.820 --> 00:16:10.260 align:middle line:84%
So how do you get up and
out of that with your mind?

00:16:10.260 --> 00:16:11.220 align:middle line:90%
Can you really do that?

00:16:11.220 --> 00:16:12.570 align:middle line:90%
>>HOLDEN: Not by yourself.

00:16:12.570 --> 00:16:14.850 align:middle line:84%
No, I don't think you
can do it by yourself.

00:16:14.850 --> 00:16:16.130 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Very realistic answer.

00:16:16.130 --> 00:16:17.713 align:middle line:84%
>>HOLDEN: Yeah, I
don't think you can.

00:16:17.713 --> 00:16:19.810 align:middle line:84%
I think, actually, the
purpose of healing,

00:16:19.810 --> 00:16:25.360 align:middle line:84%
fundamentally, is to--
at the most basic level,

00:16:25.360 --> 00:16:28.449 align:middle line:84%
it's to overcome our
sense of separateness.

00:16:28.449 --> 00:16:29.740 align:middle line:90%
That's at the most basic level.

00:16:29.740 --> 00:16:30.650 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That's a great point.

00:16:30.650 --> 00:16:31.060 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:16:31.060 --> 00:16:32.934 align:middle line:84%
>>HOLDEN: You take
something like depression.

00:16:32.934 --> 00:16:37.100 align:middle line:84%
I think depression is probably
the most widespread diagnosis

00:16:37.100 --> 00:16:40.130 align:middle line:84%
on the planet, and I would
also say the most unhelpful

00:16:40.130 --> 00:16:42.450 align:middle line:84%
diagnosis on the planet,
because when you really

00:16:42.450 --> 00:16:45.687 align:middle line:84%
look at depression, it
doesn't even mean anything.

00:16:45.687 --> 00:16:47.520 align:middle line:84%
I mean, really, just
take a look at the word

00:16:47.520 --> 00:16:49.610 align:middle line:84%
as if you've never seen
it before-- "depressed."

00:16:49.610 --> 00:16:50.662 align:middle line:90%
What's that?

00:16:50.662 --> 00:16:51.995 align:middle line:90%
I mean, it's not even a feeling.

00:16:51.995 --> 00:16:53.605 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: It means
to put down, right?

00:16:53.605 --> 00:16:54.480 align:middle line:90%
>>HOLDEN: Well, yeah.

00:16:54.480 --> 00:16:57.614 align:middle line:84%
You have to say,
is that what it is?

00:16:57.614 --> 00:16:59.780 align:middle line:84%
And then what I think you
have to do with depression

00:16:59.780 --> 00:17:04.710 align:middle line:84%
is almost go behind the
feeling or behind the word

00:17:04.710 --> 00:17:07.369 align:middle line:84%
and say, give me
another word for it.

00:17:07.369 --> 00:17:09.220 align:middle line:84%
And then what happens
is, most often,

00:17:09.220 --> 00:17:12.440 align:middle line:84%
people will talk about
something like, I feel down,

00:17:12.440 --> 00:17:17.410 align:middle line:84%
or I feel isolated,
or I feel hopeless.

00:17:17.410 --> 00:17:19.384 align:middle line:84%
Now we've got
something to work with,

00:17:19.384 --> 00:17:21.050 align:middle line:84%
because we can deal
with those feelings.

00:17:21.050 --> 00:17:24.540 align:middle line:84%
But purely when it's depressed,
I would say it's too vague.

00:17:24.540 --> 00:17:28.940 align:middle line:84%
So we need to get more intimate
with the feeling in a way.

00:17:28.940 --> 00:17:30.910 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So the word
itself is disconnecting.

00:17:30.910 --> 00:17:31.826 align:middle line:90%
>>HOLDEN: Yeah, it is.

00:17:31.826 --> 00:17:33.050 align:middle line:90%
Exactly what it is.

00:17:33.050 --> 00:17:35.040 align:middle line:84%
I think that's a really
good way of putting it,

00:17:35.040 --> 00:17:38.230 align:middle line:84%
because once it's
just depressed,

00:17:38.230 --> 00:17:40.230 align:middle line:84%
it's almost we feel
so hopeless about it,

00:17:40.230 --> 00:17:43.827 align:middle line:84%
it's like all we think we
can do with it is a chemical.

00:17:43.827 --> 00:17:44.410 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:17:44.410 --> 00:17:46.610 align:middle line:84%
>>HOLDEN: Let's try something
chemical and hope it helps.

00:17:46.610 --> 00:17:48.420 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Because you want to
go outside yourself, because,

00:17:48.420 --> 00:17:50.130 align:middle line:84%
obviously, it's not
working in here.

00:17:50.130 --> 00:17:53.380 align:middle line:84%
So when your mom was going
through that depressed state,

00:17:53.380 --> 00:17:56.240 align:middle line:84%
she was disconnected
from herself.

00:17:56.240 --> 00:17:57.790 align:middle line:90%
>>HOLDEN: Exactly what it was.

00:17:57.790 --> 00:17:59.960 align:middle line:84%
In fact, I would
say, with her, there

00:17:59.960 --> 00:18:01.900 align:middle line:84%
was this huge
feeling of isolation,

00:18:01.900 --> 00:18:03.192 align:middle line:90%
a huge feeling of separateness.

00:18:03.192 --> 00:18:05.150 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Even though she
was there with somebody

00:18:05.150 --> 00:18:06.180 align:middle line:90%
loving her so much.

00:18:06.180 --> 00:18:07.670 align:middle line:90%
>>HOLDEN: Completely.

00:18:07.670 --> 00:18:08.967 align:middle line:90%
It's not a logical thing.

00:18:08.967 --> 00:18:10.050 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: No, of course not.

00:18:10.050 --> 00:18:10.770 align:middle line:90%
Of course not.

00:18:10.770 --> 00:18:12.790 align:middle line:84%
>>HOLDEN: It's more
existential than that.

00:18:12.790 --> 00:18:18.130 align:middle line:84%
I think it goes to that
place of, I feel alone.

00:18:18.130 --> 00:18:22.170 align:middle line:84%
I'm surrounded by
everyone, and I feel alone.

00:18:22.170 --> 00:18:25.950 align:middle line:84%
And it is amazing how many
of the great traditions

00:18:25.950 --> 00:18:30.880 align:middle line:84%
have pinpointed separateness
as the great delusion,

00:18:30.880 --> 00:18:34.250 align:middle line:84%
as the great problem of
existence, if you like.

00:18:34.250 --> 00:18:37.120 align:middle line:84%
It's something that,
fundamentally, I

00:18:37.120 --> 00:18:39.430 align:middle line:90%
think we need to overcome.

00:18:39.430 --> 00:18:43.860 align:middle line:84%
And for that reason, you
can't heal on your own.

00:18:43.860 --> 00:18:46.150 align:middle line:84%
In fact, I would say to
everybody, don't even

00:18:46.150 --> 00:18:48.240 align:middle line:90%
try to heal on your own.

00:18:48.240 --> 00:18:51.920 align:middle line:84%
The whole point of healing is to
connect with something greater

00:18:51.920 --> 00:18:54.070 align:middle line:84%
than your sense of
self, because it's

00:18:54.070 --> 00:18:56.652 align:middle line:84%
something greater than
your sense of self that's

00:18:56.652 --> 00:18:57.860 align:middle line:90%
going to get you out of this.

00:18:57.860 --> 00:18:59.110 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: So purpose--

00:18:59.110 --> 00:19:00.560 align:middle line:90%
>>HOLDEN: Possibly.

00:19:00.560 --> 00:19:02.310 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: --could get
you out of depression?

00:19:02.310 --> 00:19:02.660 align:middle line:90%
>>HOLDEN: Yeah.

00:19:02.660 --> 00:19:03.243 align:middle line:90%
You know what?

00:19:03.243 --> 00:19:04.876 align:middle line:90%
It could be anything.

00:19:04.876 --> 00:19:05.750 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Other people?

00:19:05.750 --> 00:19:07.290 align:middle line:90%
>>HOLDEN: It's other people.

00:19:07.290 --> 00:19:08.933 align:middle line:84%
I mean, honestly, it
could be your cat.

00:19:08.933 --> 00:19:10.200 align:middle line:90%
It could be your dog.

00:19:10.200 --> 00:19:13.345 align:middle line:84%
It could be-- have you ever
seen "Shirley Valentine?"

00:19:13.345 --> 00:19:15.220 align:middle line:84%
You ever seen that movie?
"Shirley Valentine"

00:19:15.220 --> 00:19:19.370 align:middle line:84%
is a story of a woman who
goes through a midlife crisis.

00:19:19.370 --> 00:19:22.640 align:middle line:84%
And she has a relationship
with her wall.

00:19:22.640 --> 00:19:24.420 align:middle line:90%
She speaks to her wall.

00:19:24.420 --> 00:19:25.115 align:middle line:90%
Hi, wall.

00:19:25.115 --> 00:19:25.948 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: For weaving?

00:19:25.948 --> 00:19:27.084 align:middle line:90%
>>HOLDEN: No, this wall.

00:19:27.084 --> 00:19:27.750 align:middle line:90%
Wall, literally.

00:19:27.750 --> 00:19:29.110 align:middle line:90%
I'm speaking to my wall now.

00:19:29.110 --> 00:19:29.510 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh, OK.

00:19:29.510 --> 00:19:31.093 align:middle line:84%
>>HOLDEN: I need to
speak to somebody.

00:19:31.093 --> 00:19:34.355 align:middle line:84%
Like Tom Hanks spoke
to-- was it Nelson?

00:19:34.355 --> 00:19:34.980 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wilson.

00:19:34.980 --> 00:19:35.688 align:middle line:90%
>>HOLDEN: Wilson.

00:19:35.688 --> 00:19:36.390 align:middle line:90%
That's it.

00:19:36.390 --> 00:19:39.940 align:middle line:84%
You've got to talk to something
other than your sense of self.

00:19:39.940 --> 00:19:41.930 align:middle line:84%
It almost doesn't
matter, so long

00:19:41.930 --> 00:19:43.712 align:middle line:84%
as you're getting out
of your self image.

00:19:43.712 --> 00:19:45.920 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: It's interesting
you use those two analogies,

00:19:45.920 --> 00:19:47.503 align:middle line:84%
that those are people
who were talking

00:19:47.503 --> 00:19:50.310 align:middle line:84%
to inanimate objects
that can't feedback.

00:19:50.310 --> 00:19:53.470 align:middle line:84%
So for example, if you were
to say your mom you loved her,

00:19:53.470 --> 00:19:55.560 align:middle line:90%
she couldn't hear you.

00:19:55.560 --> 00:20:00.750 align:middle line:84%
But she might be able to receive
more from an inanimate object--

00:20:00.750 --> 00:20:01.690 align:middle line:90%
>>HOLDEN: Possibly.

00:20:01.690 --> 00:20:02.540 align:middle line:90%
That's true.

00:20:02.540 --> 00:20:06.220 align:middle line:84%
And that's why sometimes I
think cats and dogs really work.

00:20:06.220 --> 00:20:07.620 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right, absolutely.

00:20:07.620 --> 00:20:09.619 align:middle line:84%
>>HOLDEN: I remember we
used to work on this one

00:20:09.619 --> 00:20:12.080 align:middle line:84%
particular ward in
the local hospital.

00:20:12.080 --> 00:20:15.850 align:middle line:84%
And every now and then,
they'd bring this parrot in.

00:20:15.850 --> 00:20:19.930 align:middle line:84%
And this parrot, I tell you,
it was not even a whole parrot,

00:20:19.930 --> 00:20:20.430 align:middle line:90%
really.

00:20:20.430 --> 00:20:23.450 align:middle line:84%
I mean, its wings
were all tatty.

00:20:23.450 --> 00:20:27.510 align:middle line:84%
And it was more effective
than most of the consultants.

00:20:27.510 --> 00:20:31.970 align:middle line:84%
This parrot would show up,
and people became animated.

00:20:31.970 --> 00:20:34.330 align:middle line:84%
People who hadn't
even spoken for days

00:20:34.330 --> 00:20:36.510 align:middle line:84%
would light up and
look at this parrot.

00:20:36.510 --> 00:20:38.770 align:middle line:84%
So fundamentally,
what I've learned

00:20:38.770 --> 00:20:42.260 align:middle line:84%
is that healing, at
the most basic level,

00:20:42.260 --> 00:20:47.030 align:middle line:84%
is where we find
a way to overcome

00:20:47.030 --> 00:20:49.330 align:middle line:90%
that sense of separation.

00:20:49.330 --> 00:20:52.500 align:middle line:84%
And that separation isn't just
with everyone else, ultimately.

00:20:52.500 --> 00:20:55.990 align:middle line:84%
Actually, it's with
our real stuff.

00:20:55.990 --> 00:20:58.340 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And maybe we can
connect with our real self

00:20:58.340 --> 00:21:01.210 align:middle line:84%
through a connection
with somebody else.

00:21:01.210 --> 00:21:01.979 align:middle line:90%
>>HOLDEN: Yeah.

00:21:01.979 --> 00:21:03.520 align:middle line:84%
I mean, the good
news is, Lisa, we're

00:21:03.520 --> 00:21:05.480 align:middle line:84%
already connected
to our real self.

00:21:05.480 --> 00:21:07.239 align:middle line:84%
So that's why it's
possible for everyone.

00:21:07.239 --> 00:21:08.530 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: We just need reminders.

00:21:08.530 --> 00:21:09.155 align:middle line:90%
>>HOLDEN: Yeah.

00:21:09.155 --> 00:21:10.320 align:middle line:90%
Whatever works.

00:21:10.320 --> 00:21:12.710 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So what happens if
you're in a place of crisis,

00:21:12.710 --> 00:21:16.280 align:middle line:84%
where you're going along
fine, and then an accident,

00:21:16.280 --> 00:21:19.490 align:middle line:84%
or you open a tax bill
you didn't expect,

00:21:19.490 --> 00:21:25.320 align:middle line:84%
or the death of a loved
one happens instantly?

00:21:25.320 --> 00:21:27.880 align:middle line:84%
And that leads to the
cycles of depression.

00:21:27.880 --> 00:21:29.810 align:middle line:84%
So we're talking
about happiness here.

00:21:29.810 --> 00:21:32.930 align:middle line:84%
This is the point
of the interview.

00:21:32.930 --> 00:21:36.960 align:middle line:84%
How do you get happy from
those really devastating blows?

00:21:36.960 --> 00:21:40.000 align:middle line:84%
>>HOLDEN: OK, well, I
think, fundamentally,

00:21:40.000 --> 00:21:43.830 align:middle line:84%
what we have to do
is we have to move

00:21:43.830 --> 00:21:47.740 align:middle line:84%
beyond a face-off between
happiness and unhappiness,

00:21:47.740 --> 00:21:49.390 align:middle line:84%
because when you
create this face-off,

00:21:49.390 --> 00:21:51.765 align:middle line:84%
it's like, all right, OK,
if I'm going to be happy,

00:21:51.765 --> 00:21:54.090 align:middle line:90%
then I must never be unhappy.

00:21:54.090 --> 00:21:56.120 align:middle line:84%
And what we try to
do is we try to walk

00:21:56.120 --> 00:21:57.509 align:middle line:90%
on the bright side of the road.

00:21:57.509 --> 00:21:59.800 align:middle line:84%
And we say, I'm never going
to look at the unhappiness.

00:21:59.800 --> 00:22:00.740 align:middle line:84%
That's the way I'm
going to do it.

00:22:00.740 --> 00:22:02.500 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to be a
positive thinker.

00:22:02.500 --> 00:22:05.320 align:middle line:84%
Which is really hard
in England, by the way.

00:22:05.320 --> 00:22:06.687 align:middle line:90%
It may be easier in America.

00:22:06.687 --> 00:22:08.770 align:middle line:84%
But it's like, I'm going
to be a positive thinker.

00:22:08.770 --> 00:22:10.230 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to go on the
bright side of the road,

00:22:10.230 --> 00:22:12.056 align:middle line:84%
and I'm never going
to be unhappy.

00:22:12.056 --> 00:22:12.680 align:middle line:90%
And guess what?

00:22:12.680 --> 00:22:14.380 align:middle line:90%
That unhappiness, it haunts you.

00:22:14.380 --> 00:22:18.450 align:middle line:84%
It haunts you in ways that,
fundamentally, it will get you.

00:22:18.450 --> 00:22:25.620 align:middle line:84%
Therefore, true happiness is
not the absence of unhappiness.

00:22:25.620 --> 00:22:30.600 align:middle line:84%
True happiness is the capacity
to handle your unhappiness

00:22:30.600 --> 00:22:35.100 align:middle line:84%
honestly and fundamentally
with love and acceptance.

00:22:35.100 --> 00:22:38.059 align:middle line:84%
You have to find a way to
bring them all together.

00:22:38.059 --> 00:22:39.600 align:middle line:84%
And that, for me,
is the great thing.

00:22:39.600 --> 00:22:41.690 align:middle line:84%
So we ended up, on
the Happiness Project,

00:22:41.690 --> 00:22:43.890 align:middle line:84%
talking about what I
call the big happiness,

00:22:43.890 --> 00:22:48.580 align:middle line:84%
the big happiness that holds
you when you're flying high,

00:22:48.580 --> 00:22:50.930 align:middle line:84%
but also the big
happiness that holds you

00:22:50.930 --> 00:22:53.950 align:middle line:84%
when you're on your knees, the
big happiness that holds you

00:22:53.950 --> 00:22:58.040 align:middle line:84%
even when everything
appears to be falling apart,

00:22:58.040 --> 00:23:01.740 align:middle line:84%
the big happiness that helps
you to see that what's falling

00:23:01.740 --> 00:23:05.835 align:middle line:84%
apart isn't the real you;
it's your self image.

00:23:05.835 --> 00:23:09.740 align:middle line:84%
Now, that's bad enough, but at
least it's not the real you.

00:23:09.740 --> 00:23:13.250 align:middle line:84%
And the big
happiness, somehow, it

00:23:13.250 --> 00:23:17.500 align:middle line:84%
gives us that perspective to be
able to meet that unhappiness

00:23:17.500 --> 00:23:21.820 align:middle line:84%
honestly, to not call
that unhappiness negative.

00:23:21.820 --> 00:23:24.412 align:middle line:84%
We call emotions
negative emotions.

00:23:24.412 --> 00:23:26.245 align:middle line:84%
There's no such thing
as a negative emotion.

00:23:26.245 --> 00:23:28.450 align:middle line:84%
There's just emotions
we judge as negative.

00:23:28.450 --> 00:23:29.560 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:23:29.560 --> 00:23:32.950 align:middle line:84%
>>HOLDEN: But we learn
little tricks along the way.

00:23:32.950 --> 00:23:34.264 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That's a good one.

00:23:34.264 --> 00:23:35.930 align:middle line:84%
>>HOLDEN: Well, one
of the little tricks

00:23:35.930 --> 00:23:38.890 align:middle line:84%
I learned along the way--
and this is so simple, Lisa.

00:23:38.890 --> 00:23:40.280 align:middle line:90%
And this wouldn't help everyone.

00:23:40.280 --> 00:23:41.810 align:middle line:90%
But it helped me.

00:23:41.810 --> 00:23:45.290 align:middle line:84%
There's an old Buddhist trick,
which is, when you're unhappy,

00:23:45.290 --> 00:23:49.910 align:middle line:84%
when you're sad, when you're
angry, you don't say, I am sad,

00:23:49.910 --> 00:23:51.530 align:middle line:90%
I am angry.

00:23:51.530 --> 00:23:57.340 align:middle line:84%
You say, I am with
sadness, I am with anger.

00:23:57.340 --> 00:24:00.500 align:middle line:84%
Now, that might sound like
semantics to one or two people.

00:24:00.500 --> 00:24:04.070 align:middle line:84%
But to me, what that helped me
to do with my own relationship

00:24:04.070 --> 00:24:06.650 align:middle line:84%
with emotions was
to be able just

00:24:06.650 --> 00:24:09.920 align:middle line:90%
to see that I'm not that anger.

00:24:09.920 --> 00:24:11.460 align:middle line:90%
That's an experience I'm having.

00:24:11.460 --> 00:24:13.370 align:middle line:90%
But it's not my identity.

00:24:13.370 --> 00:24:15.470 align:middle line:84%
Now, if it's not my
identity, maybe there's

00:24:15.470 --> 00:24:18.830 align:middle line:84%
something bigger in me that
can meet that sadness, that

00:24:18.830 --> 00:24:21.560 align:middle line:84%
can meet that anger and
do something about it.

00:24:21.560 --> 00:24:23.310 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: That is a great
point, because you

00:24:23.310 --> 00:24:25.390 align:middle line:84%
don't identify with
it and make yourself

00:24:25.390 --> 00:24:28.079 align:middle line:84%
that depression or that
anger or that whatever.

00:24:28.079 --> 00:24:28.870 align:middle line:90%
Yes, it gives you--

00:24:28.870 --> 00:24:30.536 align:middle line:84%
>>HOLDEN: It's an
experience I'm having.

00:24:30.536 --> 00:24:31.380 align:middle line:90%
But it's not me.

00:24:31.380 --> 00:24:33.530 align:middle line:84%
And if it's not me,
then maybe, as I say,

00:24:33.530 --> 00:24:35.814 align:middle line:84%
there's something else in
me that can handle this.

00:24:35.814 --> 00:24:37.480 align:middle line:84%
By the way, as we're
talking about this,

00:24:37.480 --> 00:24:40.590 align:middle line:84%
I've got to tell you a story
about Bo, my daughter Bo.

00:24:40.590 --> 00:24:43.120 align:middle line:84%
Because Bo, she's,
like, seven now.

00:24:43.120 --> 00:24:46.160 align:middle line:84%
And what I love
about children is

00:24:46.160 --> 00:24:50.250 align:middle line:84%
that children can
experience all the emotions

00:24:50.250 --> 00:24:51.125 align:middle line:90%
inside half an hour--

00:24:51.125 --> 00:24:51.708 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Fully.

00:24:51.708 --> 00:24:53.040 align:middle line:90%
>>HOLDEN: --and still be OK.

00:24:53.040 --> 00:24:54.530 align:middle line:90%
And I love how they can do that.

00:24:54.530 --> 00:24:55.540 align:middle line:90%
Do you know what I mean?

00:24:55.540 --> 00:24:59.430 align:middle line:84%
They're amazing how they can
feel every single feeling

00:24:59.430 --> 00:25:01.990 align:middle line:84%
and just come out of
it inside half an hour

00:25:01.990 --> 00:25:05.580 align:middle line:84%
and still be their glorious,
happy, adorable selves.

00:25:05.580 --> 00:25:09.930 align:middle line:84%
And literally, just the other
day, I was having a shower.

00:25:09.930 --> 00:25:14.280 align:middle line:84%
Bo runs up to me, and
she's all Italian.

00:25:14.280 --> 00:25:15.440 align:middle line:10%
She's all emotional.

00:25:15.440 --> 00:25:17.200 align:middle line:10%
She's having a tantrum.

00:25:17.200 --> 00:25:20.450 align:middle line:10%
And she is going for it.

00:25:20.450 --> 00:25:24.070 align:middle line:84%
And she's just having this
huge, huge experience.

00:25:24.070 --> 00:25:31.360 align:middle line:84%
And basically, I look at her,
and I hum the first few bars

00:25:31.360 --> 00:25:35.722 align:middle line:84%
of Will Ferrell's-- sorry,
Pharrell Williams' "Happy."

00:25:35.722 --> 00:25:36.430 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh, yeah.

00:25:36.430 --> 00:25:37.804 align:middle line:84%
>>HOLDEN: That's
all I had to do,

00:25:37.804 --> 00:25:40.250 align:middle line:90%
the first few bars of "Happy."

00:25:40.250 --> 00:25:43.770 align:middle line:84%
And within moments, she's gone
from tantrum to boogieing.

00:25:43.770 --> 00:25:46.270 align:middle line:84%
And she's like that,
and she's happy.

00:25:46.270 --> 00:25:49.540 align:middle line:84%
And I loved how she
could make that switch

00:25:49.540 --> 00:25:50.910 align:middle line:90%
inside just a few seconds.

00:25:50.910 --> 00:25:51.910 align:middle line:90%
Do you know what I mean?

00:25:51.910 --> 00:25:52.620 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That is a great idea.

00:25:52.620 --> 00:25:54.450 align:middle line:84%
>>HOLDEN: And it's
like, oh my god.

00:25:54.450 --> 00:25:58.430 align:middle line:84%
I hope for you, Bo, that you
have that for your whole life,

00:25:58.430 --> 00:26:00.940 align:middle line:84%
because that's
fundamentally what we're

00:26:00.940 --> 00:26:02.490 align:middle line:84%
trying to do for
each other is just

00:26:02.490 --> 00:26:05.780 align:middle line:84%
to see that these emotions
are big, and they're powerful,

00:26:05.780 --> 00:26:07.800 align:middle line:84%
and they're real, and
they're to be honored.

00:26:07.800 --> 00:26:10.760 align:middle line:84%
But because they're not us,
there's something bigger in us

00:26:10.760 --> 00:26:12.180 align:middle line:90%
that can handle all of those.

00:26:12.180 --> 00:26:13.471 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: You said a great quote.

00:26:13.471 --> 00:26:15.570 align:middle line:84%
You said, "Happiness is
nowhere and right here

00:26:15.570 --> 00:26:17.462 align:middle line:90%
at the same time."

00:26:17.462 --> 00:26:19.670 align:middle line:84%
And that explains what you
were just telling us about

00:26:19.670 --> 00:26:22.940 align:middle line:84%
with her, that the
happiness was nowhere,

00:26:22.940 --> 00:26:24.870 align:middle line:84%
but then it was right
here at the same time.

00:26:24.870 --> 00:26:25.510 align:middle line:84%
>>HOLDEN: Yeah,
it's always here.

00:26:25.510 --> 00:26:26.740 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: If we could
all be like that.

00:26:26.740 --> 00:26:28.198 align:middle line:84%
>>HOLDEN: Happiness
is always here.

00:26:28.198 --> 00:26:29.860 align:middle line:84%
The problem is we're
not always here.

00:26:29.860 --> 00:26:33.710 align:middle line:84%
So happiness doesn't come and
go, not the real happiness.

00:26:33.710 --> 00:26:34.930 align:middle line:90%
Joy doesn't come and go.

00:26:34.930 --> 00:26:36.920 align:middle line:90%
It's us that comes and goes.

00:26:36.920 --> 00:26:38.850 align:middle line:90%
We're the ones that get manic.

00:26:38.850 --> 00:26:40.220 align:middle line:90%
We're the ones that get busy.

00:26:40.220 --> 00:26:43.180 align:middle line:84%
We're the ones that run
off chasing the happiness.

00:26:43.180 --> 00:26:47.314 align:middle line:84%
When we come back to ourselves,
that's when we find happiness.

00:26:47.314 --> 00:26:47.980 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Exactly.

00:26:47.980 --> 00:26:49.830 align:middle line:84%
There is a clip here
where Robert Holden

00:26:49.830 --> 00:26:51.731 align:middle line:84%
is talking on "Good
Morning, America."

00:26:51.731 --> 00:26:52.230 align:middle line:90%
Take a look.

